One Command Line Plot - Tracer R

Walter Xie

10/02/2017

Introduction

One of the feature of ComMA package is to simplify ggplot2 codes into one-line functions, and also to provide some other useful utility functions.

library(ComMA)
#getwd()

Load a MCMC log

Load a MCMC log from ../data-raw/star.beast.log, the default to move the 1st data column into row.names, but using row.names=NULL to automatically generate row names and keep the 1st column in the data object:

mcmc.log <- readMCMCLog("../data-raw/star.beast.log")
## 
## Upload MCMC log : 18 parameters excluding row names from column 1, 2001 samples excluding column names from row 1, from file ../data-raw/star.beast.log
names(mcmc.log)
##  [1] "posterior"                 "likelihood"               
##  [3] "prior"                     "speciescoalescent"        
##  [5] "birthRate.t:Species"       "YuleModel.t:Species"      
##  [7] "TreeHeight.Species"        "TreeHeight.t:tree_0_1"    
##  [9] "TreeHeight.t:tree_0_0"     "treeLikelihood.tree_0_1"  
## [11] "treeLikelihood.tree_0_0"   "treePrior.t:tree_0_1"     
## [13] "treePrior.t:tree_0_0"      "kappa.s:tree_0_0"         
## [15] "freqParameter.s:tree_0_01" "freqParameter.s:tree_0_02"
## [17] "freqParameter.s:tree_0_03" "freqParameter.s:tree_0_04"
mcmc.log$state <- as.double(rownames(mcmc.log))
# remove burnin 10% 
burnin <- nrow(mcmc.log) * 0.1
mcmc.log <- mcmc.log[burnin:nrow(mcmc.log),]
# too many points, take the first 100 after burnin
mcmc.log100 <- mcmc.log[1:100, c("TreeHeight.Species", "state")]
mcmc.log100[1:3,]
##         TreeHeight.Species   state
## 4975000          0.6441355 4975000
## 5000000          0.7041038 5000000
## 5025000          0.6326307 5025000

Plot traces

Plot the trace of the parameter TreeHeight.Species:

lwp <- ggLineWithPoints(mcmc.log100, x.id="state", y.id="TreeHeight.Species", verbose=F)
# turns off clipping
gt.lwp <- unclip.ggplot(lwp) 
plot(gt.lwp)

Adjust line and points

Show only line:

ggLineWithPoints(mcmc.log100, x.id="state", y.id="TreeHeight.Species", line.or.point=1, verbose=F)

Show only points:

ggLineWithPoints(mcmc.log100, x.id="state", y.id="TreeHeight.Species", line.or.point=2, 
                 point.size=1, verbose=F)

Kernel density estimate

require(reshape2)
df.melt <- melt(mcmc.log, id="state")
# rename column "variable" to "parameters"
colnames(df.melt)[which(names(df.melt) == "variable")] <- "parameters"
# 3 TreeHeight
df.TreeHeight <- df.melt[grep("TreeHeight", df.melt[,"parameters"]),]
unique(df.TreeHeight$parameters)
## [1] TreeHeight.Species    TreeHeight.t:tree_0_1 TreeHeight.t:tree_0_0
## 18 Levels: posterior likelihood prior ... freqParameter.s:tree_0_04
df.TreeHeight[1:3,]
##         state         parameters     value
## 10807 4975000 TreeHeight.Species 0.6441355
## 10808 5000000 TreeHeight.Species 0.7041038
## 10809 5025000 TreeHeight.Species 0.6326307

KDE for 3 parameters having the TreeHeight keyword:

ggDensityEstimate(df.TreeHeight, x.id="value", colour.id="parameters", verbose=F)

Fill in colour:

ggDensityEstimate(df.TreeHeight, x.id="value", fill.id="parameters", colour.id="parameters", verbose=F)

Stacked density plot to lose marginal densities:

ggDensityEstimate(df.TreeHeight, x.id="value", fill.id="parameters", density.pos="stack", density.alpha=1, verbose=F)

Conditional density plot to preserve marginal densities:

ggDensityEstimate(df.TreeHeight, x.id="value", y.id="..count..", fill.id="parameters", density.pos="stack", density.alpha=1, verbose=F)

Percentage scale:

ggDensityEstimate(df.TreeHeight, x.id="value", fill.id="parameters", density.pos="fill", density.alpha=1, verbose=F)
